its fifth President of the United States.

1811
01:44:31,765 --> 01:44:35,701
<i>But no university, no matter how grand</i>
<i>or august in its history,</i>

1812
01:44:35,802 --> 01:44:38,327
<i>can afford to live in the past.</i>

1813
01:44:38,438 --> 01:44:42,204
<i>So, in the spirit of tomorrow,</i>

1814
01:44:42,276 --> 01:44:45,211
<i>I introduce to you today:</i>

1815
01:44:46,446 --> 01:44:48,414
The debaters from Wiley College:

1816
01:44:48,482 --> 01:44:49,847
Miss Samantha Booke,

1817
01:44:49,916 --> 01:44:51,907
Mr. James Farmer, Junior.

1818
01:44:51,985 --> 01:44:53,247
<i>[Applause]</i>

1819
01:44:53,320 --> 01:44:54,844
What?

1820
01:45:03,664 --> 01:45:07,065
Mr. Farmer will argue the first affirmative.

1821
01:45:26,286 --> 01:45:28,550
Resolved:

1822
01:45:28,622 --> 01:45:32,080
Civil disobedience is a moral weapon

1823
01:45:32,159 --> 01:45:35,094
in the fight for justice.

1824
01:45:35,162 --> 01:45:38,290
But how can disobedience
ever be moral?

1825
01:45:38,365 --> 01:45:39,730
Well, I guess that depends

1826
01:45:39,800 --> 01:45:42,633
on one's definition of the words.

1827
01:45:42,736 --> 01:45:43,725
Word.

1828
01:45:45,739 --> 01:45:48,606
In 1919, in India,

1829
01:45:48,675 --> 01:45:53,339
10,000 people gathered in Amritsar
to protest the tyranny of British rule.

1830
01:45:53,413 --> 01:45:54,471
Has it started?

1831
01:45:54,548 --> 01:45:55,606
- Shh!
- Your brother's talking.

1832
01:45:55,682 --> 01:45:56,910
Just sit down.

1833
01:45:56,983 --> 01:46:00,146
General Reginald Dyer
trapped them in a courtyard

1834
01:46:00,287 --> 01:46:05,247
and ordered his troops
to fire into the crowd for ten minutes.

1835
01:46:05,325 --> 01:46:07,350
379 died...

1836
01:46:07,394 --> 01:46:12,525
men, women, children...

1837
01:46:12,566 --> 01:46:14,295
Shot down in cold blood.

1838
01:46:14,401 --> 01:46:18,838
Dyer said he had
taught them a moral lesson.

1839
01:46:18,939 --> 01:46:22,739
Gandhi and his followers responded
not with violence

1840
01:46:22,809 --> 01:46:27,109
but with an organized
campaign of non-cooperation.

1841
01:46:27,180 --> 01:46:29,842
Government buildings were occupied.

1842
01:46:29,916 --> 01:46:32,544
<i>Streets were blocked</i>
<i>with people who refused to rise,</i>

1843
01:46:32,619 --> 01:46:35,520
<i>even when beaten by police.</i>

1844
01:46:35,589 --> 01:46:37,989
Gandhi was arrested,

1845
01:46:38,058 --> 01:46:41,357
but the British were soon
forced to release him.

1846
01:46:41,428 --> 01:46:45,558
He called it a moral victory.

1847
01:46:45,632 --> 01:46:47,964
The definition of moral:

1848
01:46:48,068 --> 01:46:52,471
Dyer's lesson or Gandhi's victory?

1849
01:46:52,539 --> 01:46:54,006
You choose.

1850
01:46:56,576 --> 01:46:58,339
<i>[Applause]</i>

1851
01:47:11,758 --> 01:47:14,955
From 1914 to 1918,

1852
01:47:15,028 --> 01:47:20,227
for every single minute
the world was at war,

1853
01:47:20,300 --> 01:47:24,293
four men laid down their lives.

1854
01:47:24,404 --> 01:47:26,838
Just think of it.

1855
01:47:26,907 --> 01:47:32,140
240 brave young men
were hurled into eternity

1856
01:47:32,212 --> 01:47:35,613
every hour of every day, of every night,

1857
01:47:35,682 --> 01:47:38,378
for four long years.

1858
01:47:40,353 --> 01:47:43,789
35,000 hours.

1859
01:47:43,857 --> 01:47:50,262
8,281,000 casualties.

1860
01:47:52,199 --> 01:47:54,030
240.

1861
01:47:55,235 --> 01:47:57,362
240.

1862
01:47:57,471 --> 01:48:01,908
240.

1863
01:48:02,075 --> 01:48:03,508
Here was a slaughter

1864
01:48:03,577 --> 01:48:07,809
immeasurably greater than
what happened at Amritsar.

1865
01:48:07,848 --> 01:48:11,340
Can there be anything moral about it?

1866
01:48:12,719 --> 01:48:14,118
Nothing...

1867
01:48:14,187 --> 01:48:16,018
except that it stopped Germany

1868
01:48:16,089 --> 01:48:17,989
from enslaving all of Europe.

1869
01:48:18,058 --> 01:48:22,927
Civil disobedience isn't moral
because it's non-violent.

1870
01:48:22,996 --> 01:48:25,965
Fighting for your country with violence

1871
01:48:26,032 --> 01:48:28,500
can be deeply moral,

1872
01:48:28,602 --> 01:48:33,767
demanding the greatest
sacrifice of all:

1873
01:48:33,874 --> 01:48:36,172
Life itself.

1874
01:48:36,243 --> 01:48:39,679
Non-violence is the mask
civil disobedience wears

1875
01:48:39,779 --> 01:48:43,306
to conceal its true face...

1876
01:48:43,383 --> 01:48:45,874
anarchy.

1877
01:48:57,330 --> 01:49:00,094
Gandhi believes one must always act

1878
01:49:00,267 --> 01:49:03,065
with love and respect
for one's opponents,

1879
01:49:03,169 --> 01:49:05,694
even if they are Harvard debaters.

1880
01:49:05,805 --> 01:49:07,272
[Laughter]

1881
01:49:07,307 --> 01:49:11,243
Gandhi also believes
that lawbreakers must accept

1882
01:49:11,311 --> 01:49:14,576
the legal consequences for their actions.

1883
01:49:14,648 --> 01:49:16,775
Does that sound like anarchy?

1884
01:49:16,850 --> 01:49:22,117
Civil disobedience is not something
for us to fear.

1885
01:49:22,188 --> 01:49:25,214
It is, after all, an American concept.

1886
01:49:25,292 --> 01:49:27,624
You see, Gandhi draws his inspiration

1887
01:49:27,694 --> 01:49:29,491
not from a Hindu scripture,

1888
01:49:29,563 --> 01:49:31,554
but from Henry David Thoreau,

1889
01:49:31,631 --> 01:49:34,156
who I believe graduated from Harvard

1890
01:49:34,267 --> 01:49:44,511
<i>and lived by a pond</i>
<i>not too far from here.</i>

1891
01:49:44,511 --> 01:49:47,708
My opponent is right about one thing.

1892
01:49:47,781 --> 01:49:50,306
Thoreau was a Harvard grad,

1893
01:49:50,383 --> 01:49:55,116
and, like many of us, a bit self-righteous.

1894
01:49:55,188 --> 01:49:57,554
[Laughter]

1895
01:49:57,624 --> 01:50:02,823
He once said, "Any man
more right than his neighbors

1896
01:50:02,862 --> 01:50:06,593
constitutes a majority of one."

1897
01:50:06,633 --> 01:50:10,364
Thoreau the idealist could never know

1898
01:50:10,470 --> 01:50:14,497
that Adolf Hitler
would agree with his words.

1899
01:50:14,608 --> 01:50:19,739
The beauty and the burden
of democracy is this:

1900
01:50:19,813 --> 01:50:25,183
No idea prevails without
the support of the majority.

1901
01:50:25,251 --> 01:50:28,084
The people decide
the moral issues of the day,

1902
01:50:28,154 --> 01:50:30,520
not a majority of one.

1903
01:50:30,590 --> 01:50:35,050
Majorities do not decide
what is right or wrong.

1904
01:50:35,128 --> 01:50:37,096
Your conscience does.

1905
01:50:37,163 --> 01:50:39,825
So why should a citizen

1906
01:50:39,899 --> 01:50:42,390
surrender his or her conscience

1907
01:50:42,502 --> 01:50:43,833
to a legislator?

1908
01:50:43,937 --> 01:50:48,101
No, we must never, ever kneel down

1909
01:50:48,174 --> 01:50:51,075
before the tyranny of a majority.

1910
01:50:51,144 --> 01:50:53,840
[Applause]

1911
01:50:56,016 --> 01:50:57,881
<i>[Applause]</i>

1912
01:50:59,519 --> 01:51:03,046
We can't decide which laws
to obey and which to ignore.

1913
01:51:03,189 --> 01:51:05,714
If we could...

1914
01:51:05,792 --> 01:51:07,419
I'd never stop for a red light.

1915
01:51:07,460 --> 01:51:09,257
[Laughter]

1916
01:51:09,295 --> 01:51:11,320
My father is one of those men

1917
01:51:11,398 --> 01:51:15,129
that stands between us and chaos:

1918
01:51:15,235 --> 01:51:17,703
A police officer.

1919
01:51:17,804 --> 01:51:23,743
I remember the day
his partner, his best friend,

1920
01:51:23,810 --> 01:51:26,472
was gunned down in the line of duty.

1921
01:51:28,481 --> 01:51:31,245
Most vividly of all,

1922
01:51:31,317 --> 01:51:34,809
I remember the expression
on my dad's face.

1923
01:51:36,923 --> 01:51:42,828
Nothing that erodes
the rule of law can be moral,

1924
01:51:42,896 --> 01:51:47,424
no matter what name we give it.

1925
01:51:49,936 --> 01:51:51,699
Bravo!

1926
01:52:35,849 --> 01:52:36,975
Why doesn't he say something?

1927
01:52:37,050 --> 01:52:38,278
Shh!

1928
01:52:54,834 --> 01:52:58,395
In Texas...

1929
01:52:58,505 --> 01:53:00,370
they lynch Negroes.

1930
01:53:02,776 --> 01:53:04,744
<i>My teammates and I

1931
01:53:04,811 --> 01:53:09,077
saw a man strung up by his neck

1932
01:53:09,115 --> 01:53:10,673
and set on fire.

1933
01:53:13,153 --> 01:53:17,214
We drove through a lynch mob,

1934
01:53:17,290 --> 01:53:20,691
pressed our faces
against the floorboard.

1935
01:53:23,830 --> 01:53:26,856
I looked at my teammates.

1936
01:53:26,933 --> 01:53:29,959
I saw the fear in their eyes...

1937
01:53:32,372 --> 01:53:35,341
and worse...

1938
01:53:35,441 --> 01:53:36,703
the shame.

1939
01:53:39,946 --> 01:53:42,540
What was this Negro's crime

1940
01:53:42,615 --> 01:53:45,049
that he should be hung, without trial,

1941
01:53:45,118 --> 01:53:47,678
in a dark forest filled with fog?

1942
01:53:47,754 --> 01:53:51,747
Was he a thief?

1943
01:53:51,825 --> 01:53:54,953
Was he a killer?

1944
01:53:55,028 --> 01:53:56,552
Or just a Negro?

1945
01:53:58,832 --> 01:54:01,460
Was he a sharecropper?

1946
01:54:01,634 --> 01:54:03,761
<i>A preacher?</i>

1947
01:54:03,870 --> 01:54:06,896
<i>Were his children waiting up for him?</i>

1948
01:54:06,940 --> 01:54:13,038
And who are we to just
lie there and do nothing?

1949
01:54:15,715 --> 01:54:20,914
No matter what he did,
the mob was the criminal.

1950
01:54:20,987 --> 01:54:24,286
But the law did nothing,

1951
01:54:24,357 --> 01:54:27,690
just left us wondering why.

1952
01:54:33,933 --> 01:54:35,798
My opponent says

1953
01:54:35,902 --> 01:54:40,066
nothing that erodes the rule
of law can be moral.

1954
01:54:40,173 --> 01:54:43,006
But there is no rule of law
in the Jim Crow South,

1955
01:54:43,076 --> 01:54:45,544
not when Negroes are denied housing,

1956
01:54:45,645 --> 01:54:48,170
turned away from schools, hospitals,

1957
01:54:48,248 --> 01:54:50,478
and not when we are lynched.

1958
01:54:55,021 --> 01:54:56,420
St. Augustine said,

1959
01:54:56,489 --> 01:55:01,017
<i>"An unjust law is no law at all,"</i>

1960
01:55:01,160 --> 01:55:02,991
which means I have a right,

1961
01:55:03,062 --> 01:55:05,724
